"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Mark chapters 10–11
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-mark-10-11.py

Christological focus for this range:
- Ch 10: Jesus moving toward Jerusalem and the cross; marriage as covenant image (Eph 5:31-32);
  the kingdom received as a child (gift, not achievement); salvation as divine impossibility
  made possible (v.27); the cup and baptism as cross language (vv.38-39); Bartimaeus's "Son
  of David" as the first Messianic public acclamation in Mark; the right answer to "What do
  you want me to do for you?" (v.51 vs. v.37)
- Ch 11: The triumphal entry fulfilling Zech 9:9 and Ps 118 Hallel; the fig tree/temple
  intercalation as enacted parable of judgment on fruitless religion (Jer 8:13); the authority
  question as the chapter's Christological climax — answered by the cross rather than by
  the Sanhedrin's recognition
- Mark 11:26 absent from best manuscripts; brief note provided
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MARK = {
  "10": {
    "1": '<p>A theme of Christ moving purposefully toward Jerusalem and the cross: "Jesus then left that place and went into the region of Judea." The Judea-and-beyond-Jordan journey is the final approach to Jerusalem; chapters 10-16 form the Passion approach section. Every step from here is a step toward the cross that ch.8-9 have predicted. The teaching that follows — marriage, children, wealth, service, the passion prediction — all take their shape from the shadow of the cross already falling over the narrative.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme of Christ as the authoritative interpreter of the law: Pharisees test Jesus with the divorce question. The "test" (<em>peirazontes</em>) places this confrontation in the sequence of Messianic tests (cf. the wilderness temptations, Matt 4:1-11). Jesus will respond by appealing above the Mosaic provision to the original creation order — a move that reveals his authority over Moses while honoring the deeper intention of God\'s law.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of Christ appealing to Moses while transcending him: "What did Moses command you?" — Jesus grounds the discussion in the Torah but will show that the Mosaic provision is a concession to human hardness, not the original divine will. The move anticipates the Sermon on the Mount pattern (Matt 5:21-48: "you have heard... but I say to you"): Christ does not abolish the law but reveals its original and ultimate intention, which the Mosaic concessions had accommodated without expressing.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme of the law as God\'s accommodation of human failure: "Moses permitted a man to write a certificate of divorce." The Pharisees cite Moses\'s provision (Deut 24:1-4) as license; Jesus will reframe it as concession. The distinction between divine permission and divine intention is a recurring pattern in biblical law: many things God permits because of human hardness are not what God purposes. Christ comes to restore what was lost, not merely to maintain what the fallen state makes necessary.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of Christ diagnosing the human condition behind the law: "It was because of your hardness of hearts that Moses wrote you this law." The hardened heart (sklērokardia) is the same condition diagnosed in the disciples (6:52, 8:17) and in Israel (Isa 6:10). The law was shaped around what human hearts, in their hardness, could manage — not what God originally intended or ultimately purposes. Christ\'s coming is to address the root: Ezekiel 36:26 promises "I will remove your heart of stone and give you a heart of flesh" — the new covenant that Christ enacts.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation of Christ grounding marriage in the creation order: "But at the beginning of creation God made them male and female" (Gen 1:27). The appeal to "the beginning of creation" is characteristic of Christ\'s hermeneutic: interpret the law in light of creation\'s original design, not in light of post-Fall accommodations. The creation of male and female as the basis for marriage points to Ephesians 5:31-32, where Paul identifies the one-flesh union as a "profound mystery" that refers to Christ and the church.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct type of Christ\'s union with the church: "For this reason a man will leave his father and mother and be united to his wife" (Gen 2:24). Paul\'s citation of this same verse in Ephesians 5:31 — "This is a profound mystery — but I am talking about Christ and the church" — makes explicit what is implicit in Christ\'s citation here: the one-flesh marriage covenant is designed to image Christ\'s covenant with his bride. The leaving-and-cleaving of marriage types the incarnation (leaving the Father to be united to humanity).</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct type of the Christ-church covenant: "the two will become one flesh... they are no longer two, but one flesh." The one-flesh union of Genesis 2:24 is the type that Paul in Ephesians 5:32 identifies as the mystery of Christ and the church. As the husband and wife become one flesh, Christ and the church are united: "members of his body" (Eph 5:30). The marriage covenant in creation was always designed to point to the covenant union of Christ and his people — a union established at the cross.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of Christ as the guardian of the covenant union he has established: "What God has joined together, let no one separate." The prohibition of human separation applies to the marriage covenant — and by extension to the Christ-church covenant: nothing can separate those whom Christ has united to himself (Rom 8:38-39: "neither death nor life... neither height nor depth... will be able to separate us from the love of God that is in Christ Jesus our Lord"). What God joins, no power can successfully divorce.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme of private Christological instruction: the disciples ask in the house about the divorce teaching — the pattern of public declaration followed by private elaboration that characterizes Mark\'s structure (7:17, 9:28). The house is the place of deeper teaching for those who follow. The kingdom\'s more demanding standards are for those who have entered it; the deeper revelation of Christ\'s teaching is given to those who persist in asking.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of Christ establishing the higher covenant standard: "Anyone who divorces his wife and marries another woman commits adultery against her." The phrase "against her" is the expansion beyond anything in Jewish law — which framed adultery as a wrong done to the husband, not the wife. Christ\'s teaching on marriage reveals the covenant faithfulness that the divine-human covenant itself embodies: God does not divorce Israel even in her unfaithfulness (Hos 2:14-23; Isa 54:5-8).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s equal application of covenant standards across gender: "If she divorces her husband and marries another man, she commits adultery." The inclusion of the woman as a moral agent with the same obligations as the man reflects both Roman legal context (where women could initiate divorce) and the consistent pattern of Christ\'s teaching: the covenant norms are not gendered. The covenant faithfulness that marriage images is a faithfulness that characterizes the covenanting God, and must characterize both covenant partners.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s welcome of those considered least: "People were bringing little children to Jesus... the disciples rebuked them." Children in the first-century world had low social status — they were legally dependents with no rights, economically unproductive, and socially insignificant. The disciples\' rebuke follows normal social logic; Jesus\'s indignation reverses it. The one who is "gentle and lowly in heart" (Matt 11:29) consistently turns toward those the powerful dismiss.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct revelation of the kingdom\'s nature and Christ\'s welcome: "Let the little children come to me, and do not hinder them, for the kingdom of God belongs to such as these." The children are the model recipients of the kingdom — not because of their innocence (scripture is clear about human nature from birth) but because of their receptivity: they receive without earning, depend without negotiating. The kingdom is received as a gift, not achieved as a reward. Christ\'s indignation at being hindered from the children is the Shepherd\'s anger at wolves blocking his flock.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation of salvation as gift received by faith: "Truly I tell you, anyone who will not receive the kingdom of God like a little child will never enter it." The child receives what is given without earning it — this is the structure of all kingdom entry. The kingdom is not achieved by doing (the rich young man\'s question in v.17: "what must I do?") but received as a gift. The contrast with the rich young man who "went away sad" (v.22) is stark: the child receives everything; the one who tries to earn it leaves with nothing.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s priestly blessing: "he took the children in his arms, placed his hands on them and blessed them." The laying of hands for blessing is the priestly gesture from Numbers 6:22-27 (the Aaronic blessing) and Genesis 48:14-20 (Jacob blessing the sons of Joseph). The Great High Priest blesses those who come to him in dependence. The arms that will be extended on the cross are first extended to embrace children — the two postures of the same blessing love.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of Christ probing the questioner\'s deepest assumption: the rich young man\'s question "what must I do to inherit eternal life?" assumes that eternal life is the reward of doing. The framing is performance-oriented: the right actions earn the right outcome. Jesus\'s engagement with him — citing the commandments (v.19), then probing the heart\'s actual attachment (v.21) — is the pastoral work of bringing a self-righteous man to the edge of his own inability. The question is right; the assumed answer is wrong.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct Christological provocation: "Why do you call me good? No one is good — except God alone." The question is not a denial of Jesus\'s goodness but a probe: if you call me good, you are claiming more than you realize, because only God is truly good. The implicit argument: Jesus is good (he will demonstrate this throughout the exchange); therefore, by the logic of the man\'s own greeting, he is making a claim about Jesus\'s divine nature. The question invites the man to think about who he is actually addressing.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme of Christ citing the law as the starting point for self-knowledge: the second table of the Decalogue — murder, adultery, theft, false testimony, defraud, honor parents — is cited as the standard the man claims to have met. The law functions as the diagnostic instrument (Rom 3:20: "through the law we become conscious of our sin"). Christ is not mocking the commandments; he is using them to expose the one commandment the man has not kept: the commandment to love God with all his heart, which the following exchange will make concrete.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A theme of self-righteous sufficiency that Christ will gently expose: "all these I have kept since I was a boy." Paul makes the same claim before his conversion (Phil 3:6: "as for legalistic righteousness, faultless"). The claim to have kept the commandments from youth is the claim of human self-sufficiency that the gospel comes to undo. Christ looks at this man with love (v.21) — not contempt — but will expose the one thing that the law-keeping has not addressed: the heart\'s deepest attachment.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s love for the one who cannot yet surrender: "Jesus looked at him and loved him" — the only place in Mark where Jesus is said to love a specific individual. The love precedes the demand; it is the ground of it. "One thing you lack: go, sell everything you have and give to the poor... then come, follow me." The invitation is total discipleship — the same invitation given to Peter, Andrew, James, and John (1:17-18, 20). Christ loves enough to tell the truth about what stands between the man and the kingdom.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A theme of the tragedy of refused discipleship: "his face fell. He went away sad, because he had great wealth." He is the only person in Mark\'s Gospel to refuse Jesus\'s direct invitation to follow him. The sadness is the sadness of one who knows what is right and chooses otherwise — not cynicism but genuine sorrow at a cost judged too high. The man is not portrayed as a villain but as a tragedy: rich in possessions, poor in the thing that matters, and aware of the lack. He goes away with the sadness of the almost-disciple.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of Christ diagnosing the idolatry of wealth: "How hard it is for the rich to enter the kingdom of God!" The difficulty is not that wealth is intrinsically evil but that it functions as a competing attachment — a functional god that makes dependence on the true God feel unnecessary. The rich young man had kept all the commandments except the first: "You shall have no other gods before me." His wealth was his god. Christ\'s teaching reverses the common Second Temple assumption that prosperity = divine favor.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of salvation as universally difficult — not just for the wealthy: "Children, how hard it is to enter the kingdom of God!" The repetition without "for the rich" is significant: the problem is not wealth specifically but the human tendency to trust any resource other than God. Wealth is the clearest example; every human being has something they trust more than God. The universality of the difficulty drives toward the universality of the solution (v.27): "with God all things are possible."</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of the impossibility of self-salvation through a hyperbolic image: "easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for someone who is rich to enter the kingdom of God." The image is deliberately absurd — there is no small "Needle\'s Eye Gate" in Jerusalem that camels could squeeze through. The point is the utter impossibility of the rich person entering by their own effort or resources. The same impossibility applies to everyone (v.24) — the camel/needle image is simply the most vivid way to say what v.27 will state: human salvation is impossible.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of the right question that the gospel answers: "Who then can be saved?" — the disciples\' question, once they understand that wealth is not an advantage, is the right question. If the rich (who have every apparent advantage) cannot save themselves, who can? The question opens the space for the gospel\'s answer: no one saves themselves; God saves. The disciples\' amazement at the impossibility is the first step toward receiving the gift. Those who know they cannot save themselves are ready to receive salvation from the one who can.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation of the gospel: "With man this is impossible, but not with God; all things are possible with God." The echo of Genesis 18:14 ("Is anything too hard for the LORD?") and Luke 1:37 ("nothing is impossible with God") places human salvation in the category of divine miracle — the birth of Isaac to the barren Sarah, the incarnation to the virgin Mary, the salvation of the humanly unsaveable. This is the gospel in one sentence: what is impossible for humans (salvation by their own effort) is possible for God. Christ is the divine possibility that resolves the human impossibility.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A theme of the cost and the call of total discipleship: Peter\'s "We have left everything to follow you!" is the testimony of actual discipleship in contrast to the rich young man\'s refusal. The disciples have done what the man could not: left livelihoods, family, securities. Peter\'s statement is not boasting but a genuine question embedded in it: has it been worth it? Christ\'s answer (vv.29-30) is that the cost of following is real but the return is superabundant.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s promise for total-surrender discipleship: "No one who has left home or brothers or sisters or mother or father or children or fields for me and the gospel" — the comprehensive list of what can be left (home, family, livelihood) makes explicit that no attachment is exempt from the claim of discipleship. "For me and the gospel" — the two are inseparable in Mark; following Christ and the gospel\'s spread are the same cause. The promise that follows (v.30) covers the entire scope of what was surrendered.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of the eschatological abundance Christ promises: "will fail to receive a hundred times as much in this present age: homes, brothers, sisters, mothers, children and fields — along with persecutions — and in the age to come eternal life." The return is a hundred times — not merely matched but multiplied. The community of disciples (the new family of Christ, 3:34-35) replaces and expands the biological family surrendered. "Along with persecutions" is uniquely Markan — the reward includes suffering, not despite suffering but within it. The eternal life of the age to come is the ultimate return on the investment of surrender.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of the kingdom\'s eschatological reversal: "many who are first will be last, and the last first." The reversal of status is a consistent theme in Christ\'s teaching (Luke 1:52-53; 13:30; 14:11; Matt 5:3-11). The rich young man (first in the world\'s order) goes away empty; those who left everything (last in the world\'s order) will be first in the kingdom. The cross is the ultimate enactment of this reversal: the one who is most last (crucified criminal) is revealed as the one who is most first (Lord of all).</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s deliberate, leading movement toward the cross: "with Jesus leading the way, and the disciples were astonished, while those who followed were afraid." The fear and astonishment of those following Jesus to Jerusalem is the appropriate response to a man who has predicted his own death and leads the way toward it without hesitation. The third passion prediction follows immediately. Christ is not dragged to the cross; he leads toward it. His determination is the determination of the one who has come "to give his life as a ransom for many" (v.45).</p>',
    "33": '<p>A direct passion prediction with precise detail: "the Son of Man will be delivered over to the chief priests and the teachers of the law. They will condemn him to death and will hand him over to the Gentiles." The specificity is remarkable: Jewish religious leaders condemning, Roman Gentiles executing. This is exactly what will happen in chapters 14-15. The three passion predictions (8:31, 9:31, 10:33-34) become progressively more detailed, as if Christ is mapping his own death with increasing precision as it approaches.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A direct passion and resurrection prediction: "who will mock him and spit on him, flog him and kill him. Three days later he will rise." Every detail of vv.33-34 will be fulfilled with precision: the mocking (15:17-20), the spitting (15:19), the flogging (15:15), the death (15:37), the resurrection (16:6). The third passion prediction is the most complete self-disclosure of Christ\'s understanding of what awaits him. He walks toward it with open eyes — the ransom-giver who sees every detail of the price he is about to pay.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A theme of the disciples seeking glory while Christ prepares for the cross: James and John\'s request immediately follows the most detailed passion prediction. The contrast is the sharpest in Mark: Christ has just described his death; they immediately ask for seats of honor. The request reveals that they have heard the words but not understood their import — they are still in the mode of Messianic triumphalism that the Caesarea Philippi confession revealed (8:32-33). They want the glory without the cross; Christ will show them that the cross is the path to glory.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s patient engagement with misguided discipleship: "What do you want me to do for you?" The same question he will ask Bartimaeus (v.51) — but the answers will be entirely different. To James and John the question exposes their ambition; to Bartimaeus it releases his faith. The question reveals the heart of the asker. Christ does not dismiss the question but takes it seriously, engaging with what is wrong in the request rather than simply refusing it.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A theme of seeking glory through association with Christ rather than through the path Christ takes: "Let one of us sit at your right and the other at your left in your glory." The request for the two seats of highest honor anticipates the two crucified rebels on Jesus\'s right and left (15:27) — the actual occupants of those positions at Jesus\'s moment of "glory" (the cross understood as enthronement). The disciples ask for what the cross will provide for the penitent; they want it without the cross.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A direct revelation of the cross as "cup" and "baptism": "Can you drink the cup I drink or be baptized with the baptism I am baptized with?" The cup of God\'s wrath is the OT image for the judgment that falls on human sin (Ps 75:8; Isa 51:17; Jer 25:15-17; cf. Gethsemane: "take this cup from me," 14:36). Baptism as immersion in suffering/death is picked up by Paul (Rom 6:3-4: "baptized into his death"). Christ asks whether they can go where he is going — into the fullness of God\'s judgment on sin. They do not yet know what they are agreeing to.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A prophecy of the disciples\' own martyrdom: "You will drink the cup I drink and be baptized with the baptism I am baptized with." James will be executed by Herod Agrippa (Acts 12:2) — the cup, fulfilled. John will suffer exile to Patmos (Rev 1:9) and other sufferings. The promise that they will share Christ\'s suffering is both a warning and an honor: to share the cup is to be identified with the one who drank it. The pattern of the disciple sharing the master\'s suffering is the pattern of all Christian martyrdom (Col 1:24).</p>',
    "40": '<p>A revelation of the Father\'s sovereign preparation of the kingdom\'s honors: "to sit at my right or left is not for me to grant. These places belong to those for whom they have been prepared." The Father prepares the honors of the kingdom; the Son does not grant them independently. This is not a limitation on Christ but a revelation of the Trinitarian ordering of the kingdom. The places of honor will be revealed at the final judgment as the Father\'s sovereign gift to those he has chosen — the reversal of human assessments of greatness (v.31).</p>',
    "41": '<p>A theme of the disciples\' rivalry and Christ\'s teaching of servant leadership: the ten\'s indignation at James and John is not righteous anger (they wanted the same thing) but competitive envy — they are indignant that the other two asked first. The incident exposes the disciples\' collective competition for status. Christ\'s response (vv.42-45) addresses not just James and John but the entire group: the pattern of greatness they are all pursuing must be replaced by the pattern of service that he embodies.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A revelation of Christ contrasting two models of authority: "those who are regarded as rulers of the Gentiles lord it over them." The Gentile ruler model — authority exercised downward through domination and compulsion — is the world\'s default pattern of power. The word <em>katakyrieousin</em> (lord it over) and <em>katexousiazousin</em> (exercise authority downward) describe authority as force flowing from the powerful to the weak. Christ is establishing a different model, one that will be embodied in what he describes in vv.43-45 and then enacts in the cross.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A direct revelation of the kingdom\'s counter-cultural authority pattern: "whoever wants to become great among you must be your servant (<em>diakonos</em>)." The word <em>diakonos</em> (servant, later deacon) describes the one who serves at table, the lowest level of household service. Greatness in the kingdom is measured by the willingness to serve, not the capacity to command. This reversal is not merely ethical advice but a Christological description: Christ himself is the <em>diakonos</em> of vv.43-45. The standard he sets is the standard he meets.</p>',
    "44": '<p>A direct revelation of Christ\'s servanthood as the kingdom\'s ultimate model: "whoever wants to be first must be slave (<em>doulos</em>) of all." The <em>doulos</em> (slave) is lower than the <em>diakonos</em> — total ownership, no rights, complete service. The escalation (servant → slave) intensifies the reversal. Christ does not just model service; he models slavery to all — giving his life for those who did not deserve it and could not repay it. The cross is the ultimate enactment of this "slavery": the free one becomes the slave for the liberation of slaves (Gal 4:4-5).</p>',
    "46": '<p>A revelation of Christ stopping for one blind beggar on the road to his death: "as Jesus and his disciples were leaving Jericho... a blind man, Bartimaeus... was sitting by the roadside begging." Jericho is the last stop before Jerusalem; the cross is imminent. Yet Jesus stops (v.49) for a blind man shouting at the side of the road. The contrast between the magnitude of what Christ is about to do (the cross) and the apparent insignificance of the individual he stops for (a blind beggar) is deliberate: the cross is for Bartimaeus, for each individual who cries out in faith.</p>',
    "47": '<p>A direct revelation of Messianic recognition by faith: "Jesus, Son of David, have mercy on me!" This is the first time in Mark that anyone publicly calls Jesus "Son of David" — the Davidic Messianic title. Bartimaeus, who cannot see with physical eyes, sees what the disciples who can see physically have not yet publicly proclaimed: Jesus is the Davidic Messiah. The cry "have mercy on me" (<em>eleēson me</em>) is the same as the Kyrie eleison of the Christian liturgy — the prayer of those who know they have nothing to offer and everything to receive from Christ.</p>',
    "48": '<p>A revelation of faith persisting against social pressure: "many rebuked him and told him to be quiet, but he shouted all the more." The crowd\'s rebuke — trying to silence the man with the most accurate Christology in the crowd — is the world\'s persistent effort to silence authentic faith. Bartimaeus\'s persistence in the face of rebuke is the pattern of all genuine faith: it does not negotiate its approach to Christ based on social approval. The intensity increases rather than decreases when the pressure to be silent is applied.</p>',
    "49": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s response to the cry of persistent faith: "Jesus stopped and said, \'Call him.\'" The one who was walking steadily toward Jerusalem and the cross stops — not for the religious leaders who would challenge his authority (11:27-28) but for a blind beggar shouting on the roadside. The stopping is a Christological revelation: the mission of the Messiah is not primarily about the institutions of power but about the individual who cries to him in faith. He stops, he attends, he heals.</p>',
    "50": '<p>A theme of radical abandonment in coming to Christ: "throwing his cloak aside, he jumped to his feet and came to Jesus." The cloak was Bartimaeus\'s only possession and his protection from cold — the one material resource a beggar had. He throws it aside to come to Jesus, unable to bring both his burden and himself. The abandonment of the cloak is the enacted image of all coming to Christ: "everything I have counted as loss for the sake of Christ" (Phil 3:8). He comes with nothing but his need.</p>',
    "51": '<p>A direct revelation through contrast: "What do you want me to do for you?" — the same question as to James and John (v.36). James and John asked for seats of honor; Bartimaeus asks to see. The right answer to "What do you want from Christ?" is not a position of status but the restoration of what is missing: sight, healing, wholeness, salvation. The contrast is the chapter\'s Christological culmination: the blind man sees what the sighted disciples have not yet fully seen — their need is for sight, not for status.</p>',
    "52": '<p>A direct revelation of Christ as Savior and the faith that receives salvation: "your faith has healed you" — the same words as to the hemorrhaging woman (5:34), using <em>sōzō</em> which means both healed and saved. "Immediately he received his sight and followed Jesus along the road." "Along the road" — the road to Jerusalem, the road to the cross. Bartimaeus is the last healing in Mark before the Passion, and he follows Jesus into the city where Jesus will die for the very sight-giving, sin-forgiving salvation that faith like Bartimaeus\'s receives.</p>'
  },
  "11": {
    "1": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Zechariah 14: "they approached Jerusalem... at the Mount of Olives." Zechariah 14:4 places the eschatological appearing of YHWH on the Mount of Olives: "his feet will stand on the Mount of Olives, east of Jerusalem." The triumphal entry approaches from the exact location of the eschatological theophany. The Mount of Olives is also the departure point for Zechariah\'s vision of the divine king entering Jerusalem. Christ\'s approach from Bethphage and Bethany on the Mount of Olives is the fulfillment of the eschatological geography.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s prophetic knowledge and the fulfillment of Zechariah 9:9: the instruction to find a colt "which no one has ever ridden" fulfills the requirement for animals used in sacred service — they must be unbroken for secular use (Num 19:2; Deut 21:3; 1 Sam 6:7). The unridden colt for the king\'s entry echoes Zechariah 9:9 ("your king comes to you, gentle and riding on a donkey, on a colt, the foal of a donkey"). Christ enters not on a war horse (the symbol of military victory) but on a humble beast — the king who comes in peace, whose weapon is himself.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s sovereign lordship even over animals and property: "the Lord needs it." The absolute, uncommented claim — "the Lord" (<em>ho kyrios</em>) needs this — is remarkable. The owner of the colt will release it because the Lord requires it. The statement is a quiet assertion of the kind of authority that belongs to the one who comes as king: all things are his, all things are available to him, all possessions serve his purposes. The one who owns no property (no place to lay his head, 8:20 Matt) exercises the authority of the one who owns all things (Ps 24:1).</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme of the word of Christ being precisely fulfilled: "they went and found a colt outside in the street, tied at a doorway, exactly as he said." The precision of prophetic fulfillment — finding everything exactly where and how Christ had said — establishes the authority of his knowledge. The word of Christ does not merely predict; it shapes reality to conform to its description. This is the pattern of incarnate Wisdom speaking: "heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will never pass away" (13:31).</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme of Christ\'s purposes meeting questions from those who do not understand: "What are you doing, untying that colt?" The question from bystanders is innocent but highlights the gap between what Christ is doing and what ordinary observers can see. The whole triumphal entry will have the same quality: the crowd sees a king entering; they do not yet see the king entering for his own crucifixion. The gap between apparent and actual meaning is the Christological irony of the Passion approach.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme of Christ\'s word being sufficient authorization: "they answered as Jesus had told them to, and the people let them go." The word of Jesus — reported secondhand — is enough to release the colt. The authorization structure previews the authorization that will govern the church\'s mission: the disciples speak what Christ has told them to say, and it opens doors. The word of Christ has inherent authority that does not require further demonstration for those who receive it.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Zechariah 9:9: "he sat on it." The king enters Jerusalem on the colt, humble and lowly — not on the war horse that a conquering military Messiah would ride (Rev 19:11 reserves that for the second coming). The cloaks thrown over the colt are the disciples\' own garments — the offering of whatever they have for the one who is coming. The entry is simultaneously royal (king entering his city) and humble (unshod beast, borrowed garments, no military escort).</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct fulfillment of the royal acclamation of 2 Kings 9:13: when Jehu was anointed king, his followers "hurried and took their cloaks and spread them under him on the bare steps." The spreading of cloaks on the road is the ancient Israelite gesture of royal homage. The Jericho pilgrims spontaneously enact the coronation gesture — they are welcoming the king, though they do not fully understand the nature of the kingship they are welcoming. The branches cut from the fields add the Feast of Tabernacles imagery (Lev 23:40), suggesting the eschatological harvest festival.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct citation of Psalm 118:25-26 (the Hallel): "Hosanna! Blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord!" Psalm 118 was the Passover Hallel psalm sung as pilgrims entered Jerusalem — the crowd is doing what pilgrims always did at this point on the road, but now applying the words to Jesus specifically. "Hosanna" (<em>hōsanna</em> from Hebrew <em>hoshia-na</em> = "Save now!") was a cry for salvation that had become a liturgical acclamation. The crowd is proclaiming Jesus as the one who comes in the divine name — the messenger of YHWH — with a prayer for salvation embedded in the acclamation.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of the crowd\'s partial understanding of Christ\'s kingship: "Blessed is the coming kingdom of our father David!" The crowd understands Jesus\'s entry as the arrival of the Davidic kingdom — they are right about the lineage (Bartimaeus has just named him Son of David) but wrong about the timing and nature. The Davidic kingdom is arriving, but it arrives through the cross rather than through military liberation. "Hosanna in the highest heaven" — the cry goes from earth to heaven, seeking the salvation that God in heaven can provide through the one who comes from heaven.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s surveying of the temple — the first act of the king in his city: "Jesus entered Jerusalem and went into the temple courts. He looked around at everything." The survey precedes the cleansing (v.15) — this is not impulsive but deliberate. The king inspects his domain. The intercalation structure (entry → survey → depart; return → fig tree cursed → temple cleansed → fig tree withered) reveals that the fig tree and the temple are the same sign. The late hour forces his departure; he will return with judgment (v.15).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of the humanity of the incarnate Christ: "Jesus was hungry." The one who fed five thousand with five loaves (6:41-44) is himself hungry on the road to Jerusalem. The incarnation is the willing limitation of divine provision to human experience — the Son of God who satisfies hunger (6:42) experiences hunger himself. Hebrews 4:15 ("we do not have a high priest who is unable to empathize with our weaknesses") grounds the priestly ministry of Christ in his experience of human vulnerability.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A type of the judgment on fruitless religion: the fig tree with leaves but no fruit. Jeremiah 8:13 (LXX) speaks of God\'s judgment on Israel: "there are no figs on the fig tree; its leaves are withered, and what I have given them has passed away." The fig tree was a consistent OT symbol for Israel (Hos 9:10; Mic 7:1; Joel 1:7). A tree that displays the outward signs of life (leaves) without producing the fruit that justifies its existence is the image of religion that performs its forms without producing the righteousness and faith the forms were meant to cultivate.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct type of Christ pronouncing judgment on fruitless religion: "May no one ever eat fruit from you again." The cursing of the fig tree is the enacted parable of judgment on the temple system that the next day\'s cleansing will make explicit. Jesus does not explain the parable immediately — the disciples hear the curse (v.14) and the next day see its effect (v.20-21). The intercalation frames the temple cleansing as the fulfillment of the fig tree judgment: the temple has leaves (sacrifice, prayer, teaching) but no fruit (righteousness, faith, justice for the nations).</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation of Christ as Lord of the temple exercising judgment: "Jesus entered the temple courts and began driving out those who were buying and selling there." The cleansing is not a reform of commerce but an enacted prophetic sign — Christ is the Lord who comes suddenly to his temple (Mal 3:1: "the Lord you are seeking will come to his temple"). The overturning of the money-changers\' tables is the judgment of the one whose house it is: "the LORD of hosts" will purify the sons of Levi (Mal 3:3). The temple belongs to the one who cleanses it.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A theme of Christ protecting the temple\'s sacred character: "he would not allow anyone to carry merchandise through the temple courts." The temple courts had become a commercial thoroughfare — a shortcut through the city. Christ\'s refusal to allow commercial traffic is the assertion of the holiness of the place — the Court of the Gentiles is not a public market but a house of prayer for all nations (v.17). The restored dignity of the temple space is the Christological action: Christ restores what human commerce had degraded.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of the cross-plot intensifying after the temple cleansing: "the chief priests and the teachers of the law heard this and began looking for a way to kill him." The triumphal entry and the temple cleansing together seal the outcome: Jesus has challenged the authority of the temple establishment in the most visible and public way possible. The plot that has been simmering (3:6; 8:31) now becomes urgent. "They feared him, because the whole crowd was amazed" — the threat is popular authority; the solution they choose is execution.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme of Christ moving between the city (confrontation) and Bethany (withdrawal): the daily rhythm of ch.11-15 — teaching in Jerusalem by day, departing by night — gives the Passion week its structure. The withdrawal to Bethany is the same pattern as the mountain for prayer (6:46) and the house for teaching (7:17): Jesus does not remain in the place of confrontation but withdraws to places of rest and instruction. The final withdrawal from Jerusalem will be the cross itself.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of the completion of the prophetic sign: the fig tree withered "from the roots" — not just the leaves but the source of life, completely and permanently. The judgment on fruitless religion is total. Peter\'s exclamation (v.21) makes the connection explicit. The withering from the roots anticipates the destruction of the temple that Jesus will predict in 13:2 ("not one stone here will be left on another") — the judgment Christ enacts symbolically on the fig tree will be enacted literally on the temple in 70 CE.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A theme of the disciples as witnesses to Christ\'s enacted word: Peter "remembered and said to Jesus, \'Rabbi, look! The fig tree you cursed has withered!\'" The disciples\' function throughout Mark is as witnesses — their testimony, including to their own failures and puzzlement, forms the Petrine tradition behind the Gospel. Peter\'s remembering (the same verb as in 14:72, Peter\'s memory of the cock-crow and his weeping after the denial) marks him as the one who traces the connections between Christ\'s words and their fulfillment.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of Christ teaching faith in God as the ground of all his actions: "Have faith in God" (<em>echete pistin theou</em> — literally "have faith of God" / "have God\'s faith") — the instruction that follows the fig tree sign is not a lesson in using faith as a tool but in trusting the God who acts in power. Everything Christ has done — the healings, the exorcisms, the cursing of the fig tree, the cleansing of the temple — is done in complete trust of the Father. The disciples are called to the same trust.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of faith in God as capable of the apparently impossible: "if anyone says to this mountain, \'Go, throw yourself into the sea,\' and does not doubt in their heart but believes that what they say will happen, it will be done." The mountain/sea image is eschatological (Isa 54:10; Zech 14:4-5; cf. Zechariah\'s eschatological geography of the Mount of Olives split and moved). Christ is not teaching a technique of positive confession but the power of genuine faith in the God who moves mountains — a power he himself embodies and has just demonstrated with the fig tree.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct revelation of prayer as participation in Christ\'s own relationship to the Father: "whatever you ask for in prayer, believe that you have received it, and it will be yours." The prayer of faith is grounded in the character and faithfulness of the Father. Christ\'s own prayer life (1:35, 6:46, 14:32-39) is the model: total dependence on the Father, total confidence in his provision. The disciples\' prayer is participation in the Son\'s ongoing conversation with the Father — an access opened by the one who is teaching them to pray.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of forgiveness as the condition for receiving forgiveness — and as the pattern of the cross: "if you hold anything against anyone, forgive them, so that your Father in heaven may forgive you your sins." The connection of human forgiveness to divine forgiveness is the Lord\'s Prayer pattern (Matt 6:12,14-15). The cross is the ground of both: Christ forgives from the cross ("Father, forgive them," Luke 23:34), and those forgiven by the cross are those who forgive as they have been forgiven. The forgiveness Christ is about to purchase enables and demands the forgiveness he teaches.</p>',
    "26": '<p>Mark 11:26 ("But if you do not forgive, neither will your Father who is in heaven forgive your trespasses") is absent from the earliest and most important manuscripts (Codex Sinaiticus, Codex Vaticanus, and other early witnesses). It is a scribal interpolation from Matthew 6:15, added to complete the thought of v.25. The MKT text at this verse reflects this textual uncertainty. The verse is not part of Mark\'s original text, though its teaching is authentically attested in Matthew.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of the formal Christological confrontation: "the chief priests, the teachers of the law and the elders came to him." All three components of the Sanhedrin — priests, scribes, and elders — gather for the authority challenge. The confrontation that follows (vv.28-33) is the formal institutional rejection of Christ by the representative body of Israel\'s religious leadership. Their "Who gave you authority?" is the central question of the Gospel — and its answer is the cross and resurrection, not their recognition.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation of the Christological question that the whole Gospel turns on: "By what authority are you doing these things? And who gave you authority to do this?" The question about authority (<em>exousia</em>) echoes the crowd\'s astonishment in 1:22 ("he taught them as one who had authority, not as the teachers of the law") and 1:27 ("with authority he gives orders to evil spirits"). The answer to "who gave you this authority" is: the Father, demonstrated by the Spirit at the baptism (1:10-11), and vindicated by the resurrection (Rom 1:4). The Sanhedrin will not hear the answer from Christ\'s lips; they will be confronted with it by the empty tomb.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of Christ answering authority with authority: Jesus\'s counter-question about John\'s baptism is not evasion but a trap that exposes the Sanhedrin\'s bad faith. If John\'s authority was from heaven (as the people believed), then John\'s testimony about Jesus (John 1:29-34) answers the question. If John\'s authority was merely human, they have no basis for the crowd\'s respect that they are trying to protect. Jesus uses the same logic they use against him: authority must come from either God or humans; which do you say?</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of Christ identifying John\'s authority as the key to his own: "John\'s baptism — was it from heaven, or of human origin?" John testified that Jesus is the one "more powerful" (1:7), the one who will baptize with the Holy Spirit (1:8), the Lamb of God (John 1:29). To acknowledge John\'s prophetic authority is to acknowledge John\'s testimony about Jesus. The question is not a change of subject but a direct answer: my authority is from the same source as John\'s — from heaven, from the Father who sent us both.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A theme of authority rejected for political reasons: "If we say, \'From heaven,\' he will ask, \'Then why didn\'t you believe him?\'" — the leaders know the right answer but refuse it because of its consequences. The refusal to acknowledge divine authority for political reasons is the pattern of all institutional rejection of Christ: not ignorance but willful suppression of what is known (Rom 1:18: "who suppress the truth by their wickedness"). They know the truth; they will not say it because the truth costs them.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A theme of leadership by fear rather than truth: "They feared the people, for everyone held that John really was a prophet." The Sanhedrin\'s decision is made by calculating public reaction, not by seeking truth. "What will the crowd say?" rather than "What is true?" is the governing question. The same calculation will govern the trial: Pilate delivers Jesus to death rather than release him because he fears the crowd (15:15). Fear of the crowd is the consistent mechanism of Christ\'s unjust condemnation.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s authority demonstrated through refusal to submit to authority that lacks integrity: "Neither will I tell you by what authority I am doing these things." The refusal is the answer: a body that makes decisions on political rather than theological grounds has forfeited the right to receive the declaration of divine authority. Christ does not submit his authority to a tribunal that has already decided to condemn him. His authority will be demonstrated by what he is about to do — not by what he tells the Sanhedrin. The cross and resurrection will be the answer to "By what authority?"</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'mark')
    merge_comm(existing, MARK)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'mark', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Mark mkt-christ chs 10-11: {total} verses total written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
